            <p>
               <mixed-citation id="d22e142" publication-type="other">
The First result concerns those fields that are paying APRT, but not PRT. The reduction in APRT
causes a reduction in their overall tax burden as long as they do not pay PRT. When they first became
liable to PRT (or APRT is repaid, in the event of PRT liability not occurring until after APRT ends)
the tax burden in that year increases (relative to the pre-budget system) by the amount which the field
had previously saved. A change in the instalment mechanism for paying PRT and APRT (with
instalments to be based on PRT before APRT is offset) means that this effect does not apply to fields
which are already paying PRT and APRT.</mixed-citation>
            </p>
